NT|^B@2|CP|8|AT|
hondo717: |CP||AT|Now as to this 2 over 1 auction. The basic idea behind 2 over 1 is that if partner bids at the 2 level over one of a major, that is a game force. And, "fast arrival" is one of the important principles that arise from 2 over 1.  Fast arrival means that the faster responder bids game, once a game force is established, the weaker responder's hand is. You want to keep the bidding lower to explore for slam, but if you have a minimum game forcing hand, no need to go slow.  On this auction, had it gone 1@S-2@D-2@H-4@S, saylee would be showing a minimum opening hand with spade support and diamonds and little interest in slam.|
PG| ***** 89 ***** |


NT|^B@2|CP|8|AT|
hondo717: |CP||AT|The auction 1@S-2@D-2@H-2@S is stronger. There is not general agreement as to 1@S-2@D-2@H-3@S.  I play that is pretty much a slam force, but others do not. So, with saylee's hand, I would have bid 2@S, not 3@S, showing some interest in slam. That auction shows saylee has around 16 points or so, which is exactly what west has. In any case, angela, with a minimum hand and little in the way of aces and kings, is not interested in slam, so would bid 4@S over 2@S. But, "fast arrival" is the important point to remember. If west forces to game and then makes minimum rebids, that shows slam interest if playing 2 over 1.|
