NT|^B@2|CP|8|AT|
hondo717: |CP||AT|So there is a good example where I pushed them into game which it turns out it can be made. Now, let me discuss my opening lead. In general, as you know, I don't like to lead unprotected aces. However, leading away from my minor suit kings did not seem very good, and indeed, if I had, it would have cost us a trick.  I could have gone passive and led a trump. However, odds are moe has the K of spades, so in this case leading the ace should be ok more times than not. In this case, moe did not have the K, but it still did not cost me a trick.|
PG| ***** 150 ***** |


NT|^B@2|CP|8|AT|
hondo717: |CP||AT|On the other hand, a heart lead would have worked also. Now, let us see how aggie might plan the hand. She can count 1 spade loser, and 1 diamond loser, pretty much however the diamonds are sitting. Even if the diamond finesse works, as it does, she still has to lose a diamond, since she is missing the K and 10. If she is lucky, she only has 1 club loser, if moe has the K of clubs. |
PG| ***** 151 ***** |


NT|^B@2|CP|8|AT|
hondo717: |CP||AT|However, she has an additional chance. If clubs are 3-2, she can set up her clubs, and pitch her diamonds. So, she should ignore diamonds until last. She should draw trumps, and then play a club to the ace and a club back towards the K. If moe has the K, then the hand makes no matter what. If I have the K, and lead a diamond, she has to hope the K of diamonds is onside, and play a low diamond. By playing clubs first, she gives herself many extra chances to make the hand. So, the idea here is to maximize your odds.|
